    <h2>What is an IPO?</h2>
    <p>
        Initial Public Offering (IPO) refers to the process where private companies sell their shares to the public 
        to raise equity capital from the public investors. The process of IPO transforms a privately-held company into 
        a public company. This process also creates an opportunity for smart investors to earn a handsome return on 
        their investments.
    </p>

    <h2>Types of IPOs</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><span class="highlight">Fixed Price Offer:</span> The company determines the price at which its shares will be sold before the IPO begins.</li>
        <li><span class="highlight">Book Building Offer:</span> The company provides a price range, and investors bid within this range to determine the final issue price.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Steps to Invest in an IPO</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Open a valid Demat and trading account linked with your bank account.</li>
        <li>Research the company and study the Draft Red Herring Prospectus (DRHP).</li>
        <li>Choose the IPO and place a bid within the price range.</li>
        <li>Allocate funds in your bank account for the IPO application.</li>
        <li>Wait for the allotment results. If allotted, shares will be credited to your Demat account.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Advantages of Investing in an IPO</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Opportunity to invest early in high-growth companies.</li>
        <li>Potential for significant returns if the company performs well in the market.</li>
        <li>Liquidity, as shares can be sold after the listing in the secondary market.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Disadvantages of Investing in IPO</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><span class="highlight">More Costs:</span> IPOs can be costly due to compliance and underwriting expenses.</li>
        <li><span class="highlight">Lesser Autonomy:</span> Public companies must answer to shareholders and a board of directors.</li>
        <li><span class="highlight">Extra Pressure:</span> Firms are under pressure to maintain stock value, which might compromise long-term planning.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Common Terms Associated with IPOs</h2>
    <div class="table-container">
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Term</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Issuer</td>
                    <td>The company issuing shares to the public.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Underwriter</td>
                    <td>Entities helping the company with the IPO process, including underwriting stocks.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Green Shoe Option</td>
                    <td>Allows underwriters to sell additional shares if demand exceeds expectations.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Price Band</td>
                    <td>The price range set by the issuer for investors to bid within.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Book Building</td>
                    <td>A method to determine the IPO price based on investor bids.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Oversubscription</td>
                    <td>Occurs when demand for shares exceeds the number of shares available.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>DRHP</td>
                    <td>Draft Red Herring Prospectus, providing details about the company and IPO.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h2>Tips for First-Time IPO Investors</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Study the company’s financial health, business model, and growth potential.</li>
        <li>Invest only if you understand the risks associated with IPOs.</li>
        <li>Consider the valuation and compare it with peers in the industry.</li>
        <li>Avoid overinvesting; diversify your portfolio to manage risk effectively.</li>
    </ul>
